      <div class="causes">
        <div> <h6> Causes & Corrections</h6> </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> What we most commonly perceive as Shoulder tension is actually an extension of neck strain from a forward leaning head position 
              (sometimes made worse by a rounding of the back). This leads to a "hunched over" posture which causes the Trapezius (aka your 
              "traps") and Pectorals (aka your "pecs") to tense up. </p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/neck_illustration1a.jpg">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/trapezius-pain.jpeg">
          <img class="short" src="images/shoulders/posture-correction.jpg">
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> Most forms of shoulder-related computer strain however, are usaually a result of tension being held between the neck and wrist. 
              If either of these areas are strained, try correcting them and see if the pain persists.</p>
          <p> If you experience shoulder pain in the mouse-arm specifically, switching to a <b>vertical mouse</b> can often help. 
              By aligning the arm in a more neutral position, you can take much of the strain off of the internal rotator muscles.</p>
        </div>        
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="long" src="images/shoulders/shoulders1.jpg">
